
                             Linux commands




1. ls -Directory listing 
2. ls -al Formatted listing with hidden files 
3. ls -lt Sorting the Formatted listing by time modification
 4. cd dir -  Change directory to dir 
5. cd- Change to home directory
 6. pwd - Show current working directory
 7. mkdir dir -  Creating a directory dir
 8. cat -  >file Places the standard input into the file
 9. more -  file Output the contents of the file 
10. head -  file Output the first 10 lines of the file 
11. tail  - file Output the last 10 lines of the file 
12. tail -f  - file Output the contents of file as it grows,starting with the last 10 lines 
13. touch -  file Create or update file 
14. rm -  file Deleting the file 15. rm -r dir Deleting the 
16. rm -f - file Force to remove the file 
17. rm -rf  - dir Force to remove the directory dir 
18. cp  - file1 file2 Copy the contents of file1 to file2 
19. cp -r dir1 dir2 Copy dir1 to dir2;create dir2 if not present 
20. mv file1 file2 Rename or move file1 to file2,if file2 is an existing directory 
21. ln -s file link Create symbolic link link to file
22.ps -To display the currently working processes 
23. top Display all running process Unix/Linux Command Reference  
24. kill pid Kill the process with given pid 
25. killall -  proc Kill all the process named proc 
26. pkill  - pattern Will kill all processes matching the pattern 
27. bg: -  List stopped or background jobs,resume a stopped job in the background 
28. fg:  - Brings the most recent job to foreground 
29. fg = :n Brings job n to the foreground
30. chmod octal -  file Change the permission of file to octal,which can be found separately for user,group,world by adding, • 4-read(r) • 2-write(w) • 1-execute(x) 
31. grep pattern  - file Search for pattern in file 
32. grep -r pattern dir Search recursively for pattern in dir 33. command | grep pattern Search pattern in the output of a command 34. locate file Find all instances of file 
35. find . -name filename Searches in the current directory (represented by a period) and below it, for files and directories with names starting with filename 
36. pgrep pattern Searches for all the named processes , that matches with the pattern and, by default, returns their ID System Info 
37. date Show the current date and time
38. cal Show this month's calender
39. uptime Show current uptime
 40. w Display who is on line 
41. whoami Who you are logged in as Unix/Linux Command Reference  
41. finger user Display information about user 
42. uname -a Show kernel information 
43. cat proc/meminfo Memory information 
44. man command Show the manual for command 
45. df Show the disk usage 
12. du Show directory space usage
 46. free Show memory and swap usage
 47. whereis app Show possible locations of app 
48. which app Show which applications will be run by default
49. cat /proc/cpuinfo Cpu information
50. tar cf file.tar file Create tar named file.tar containing file 
51. tar xf file.tar Extract the files from file.tar 
52. tar czf file.tar.gz files Create a tar with Gzip compression 
53. tar xzf file.tar.gz Extract a tar using Gzip 
54. tar cjf file.tar.bz2 Create tar with Bzip2 compression 
55. tar xjf file.tar.bz2 Extract a tar using Bzip2 
56.. gzip file Compresses file and renames it to file.gz 
57. gzip -d file.gz Decompresses file.gz back to file
58.ping host Ping host and output results 59. whois domain Get whois information for domains 
60. dig domain Get DNS information for domain 
61. dig -x host Reverse lookup host 
62. wget file Download file
 63. wget -c file Continue a stopped download
64.ctrl+c Halts the current command 
65. ctrl+z Stops the current command, resume with fg in the foreground or bg in the background
 66. ctrl+d Logout the current session, similar to exit 
67. ctrl+w Erases one word in the current line 
68. ctrl+u Erases the whole line 
69. ctrl+r Type to bring up a recent command 
70. !! Repeats the last command 
71. exit Logout the current session


